  "prompt": "What is the difference between product design and industrial design?",
  "response": "While product design and industrial design are closely related and sometimes used interchangeably, there are some key differences:\n\nProduct Design:\n1. Broader focus on the entire user experience\n2. Emphasizes functionality, user needs, and problem-solving\n3. Often involves digital and physical product development\n4. Can include software, apps, and digital interfaces\n5. More centered on the product's purpose and user interaction\n\nIndustrial Design:\n1. More specific focus on physical product aesthetics and manufacturing\n2. Emphasizes visual design, form, and physical manufacturing processes\n3. Concentrates on the physical appearance and ergonomics of objects\n4. Typically deals with physical consumer goods and manufactured products\n5. Strong emphasis on aesthetics, materials, and production techniques\n\nOverlap:\n- Both disciplines aim to create user-friendly, visually appealing products\n- Both require understanding of user needs and technical constraints\n- Both involve creating solutions that balance form and function\n\nIn practice, many designers work across both disciplines, and the boundaries are often blurred. The main difference is that industrial design tends to be more focused on physical product design, while product design has a broader, more holistic approach to solving user problems.",
